<tr>
          <td background="/newimages/backgrounds/middlecolumn_black.gif" valign="top">
                         <!--First page-->
            <!--First page-->
            <!--First page-->
            <table width="491" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
              <tr>
                <td background="/newimages/articles/resize.gif" valign="top"><img src="/newimages/articles/blueborder.gif" width="1" height="86"></td>
                <td background="/newimages/articles/resize.gif" valign="top">
                  <img src="/php-bin/getimage.inc?id=133472"></td>
                <td valign="top" bgcolor="#000000"><img src="/newimages/misc/85border.gif" width="3" height="86"></td>
                <td bgcolor="#000000" valign="top" width="100%">
                  <TABLE width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#000000" height="40">
                    <TR>
                      <TD nowrap class="smalltext" height="21">&nbsp;&nbsp;<SPAN class="bluebolded">Victim: </SPAN>Rick Goodman&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
                    </TR>
                    <TR>
                      <TD nowrap class="smalltext" height="21">&nbsp;&nbsp;<SPAN class="bluebolded">Position: </SPAN>Developer&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
                    </TR>
                    <TR>
                      <TD nowrap class="smalltext" height="21">&nbsp;&nbsp;<SPAN class="bluebolded">Company: </SPAN> <A href="http://www.stainlesssteelstudios.com/" class="brightlinks">Stainless Steel Studios</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
                    </TR>
                    <TR>
                      <TD nowrap class="smalltext" height="22">&nbsp;&nbsp;<SPAN class="bluebolded">Subject: </SPAN>Empire Earth&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
                    </TR>
                  </TABLE>
              </tr>
            </table>
            <TABLE width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
              <TR>
                <TD><IMG src="/newimages/misc/492blueborder.gif" width="492" height="1"></TD>
              </TR>
            </TABLE>
            <TABLE width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="12">
              <TR valign="top">
                <TD class="smalltext">Rick was in on the Age of Empires development team but has now made his own game called Empire Earth.  Here's his story.</TD>
              </TR>
            </TABLE>
            <TABLE width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="12">
              <TR>
                <TD>
                  <SPAN class="Headline">Empire Earth</SPAN>
                  <P>   <b> MGON: You were the lead designer for Age of Empires at Ensemble Studios. What did you learn from the design of that game what have you carried on to Empire Earth. </b><br />
<br />
Working on Age of Empires® at Ensemble Studios was a wonderful experience.  I learned a lot from the project.  I also learned a lot about the business side of game development.  Once Age of Empires was finished, I had a very clear vision about what I wanted to do next, and so did Ensemble.  So we amicably parted company so that we could each pursue our own goals.<br />
<br />
<b> MGON: Were you surprised at the great success Age of Empires was? </b><br />
<br />
To be honest I was.  I thought we had a great game on our hands, but it’s a bit humbling when so many other people agree!<br />
<br />
<b> MGON: Obviously you have a past in real time strategy gaming, but what gave you the idea to develop a game which spans so many historical eras? </b><br />
<br />
I have always enjoyed history.  It is a fascinating subject and with Age of Empires I was able to take my love of history and incorporate it into a game.  The idea for doing Empire Earth came from the experience of working on Age of Empires.<br />
<br />
<b> MGON: Is the campaign section of the game based around actual battle such as the Battle of Waterloo and other historically documented events? </b><br />
<br />
The first three campaigns are historically based – they each follow the exciting rise to power of a well-known historical civilization.  The civilizations are Ancient Greece, England and Germany.  The fourth campaign is set in the future and involves a bid to make Russia a world power once again.<br />
<br />
The campaigns are divided into scenarios, and each scenario has its own goals and objectives.  Occasionally, you are rewarded with “Civ Points” with which you can purchase bonuses for your civilization, and these bonuses carry over to the next scenario.  The scenarios also contain dramatic cut scenes – movie-like sequences which help tell the story.<br />
<br />
We should mention that all the scenarios in Empire Earth were created with the built-in scenario editor.  We think this is the best scenario editor ever created for an RTS game.  We can’t wait to see what kinds of scenarios and campaigns people in the gaming community come up with!<br />
<br />
<b> MGON: With Empire Earth it has been said realism is important. Was much research done regarding the epochs set in the past? How did you approach the concept of telling the future in terms of technology and battle? </b><br />
<br />
We spent a lot of time doing research for the game, but realism always took a back seat to fun whenever the two were at odds.  As a result, we think Empire Earth is very fun to play.  If the game also encourages players to learn more about history on their own, so much the better.<br />
<br />
The future Epochs in Empire Earth are based a little on science and a little on science fiction.  We wanted to continue the history of Earth into the future, so we created a story for it.  Gamers can play through that story in the fourth and final single player campaign.  They can also play the future Epochs in a random map game in both single and multiplayer.<br />
<br />
<b> MGON: The beta testing period was used to test the multiplayer aspect of the game. How much has changed since the first beta version with regards to unit balance and map size etc and in your opinion was the Beta test successful or a waste of time? </b><br />
<br />
The Beta program was a great success.  We got some great feedback and the testers got a chance to sample the game before it shipped.  The finished product is that much better because of the excellent work of our many beta testers.<br />
<br />
<b> MGON: Are all the campaigns in Empire Earth resource based or will some only offer a limited amount of units to complete the mission? </b><br />
<br />
The scenarios in the campaigns are very diverse, offering many different gaming experiences.  Some require resource gathering, some do not.  Some give an army to the player, some do not.  Players will see a lot of variety in the scenarios – there’s really something for everyone.  There are also 8 learning scenarios to teach players the basics of the game.<br />
<br />
</P>
                </TD>
              </TR>
            </TABLE>
